05070nam a22005775i 9780822385509DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223855097 a10.1515/97808223855092doi  a(DE-B1597)551902  a(OCoLC)1027512685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF5000 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a972.94/032221 aFischer, Sibylle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModernity Disavowed :bHaiti and the Cultures of Slavery in the Age of Revolution /cSibylle Fischer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (382 p.) :b10 illus., 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Truncations of Modernity -- tPART I Cuba -- t1 The Deadly Hermeneutics of the Trial of José Antonio Aponte -- t2 Civilization and Barbarism: Cuban Wall Painting -- t3 Beyond National Culture, the Abject: The Case of Plácido -- t4 Cuban Antislavery Narratives and the Origins of Literary Discourse -- tPART II Santo Domingo/The Dominican Republic -- t5 Memory, Trauma, History -- t6 Guilt and Betrayal in Santo Domingo -- t7 What Do the Haitians Want? -- t8 Fictions of Literary History -- tPART III Saint Domingue/Haiti -- t9 Literature and the Theater of Revolution -- t10 ''General Liberty, or The Planters in Paris'' -- t11 Foundational Fictions: Postrevolutionary Constitutions I -- t12 Life in the Kingdom of the North -- t13 Liberty and Reason of State: Postrevolutionary Constitutions II -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Imperial Constitution of Haiti, 1805 -- tAppendix B. Chronology -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModernity Disavowed is a pathbreaking study of the cultural, political, and philosophical significance of the Haitian Revolution (1791-1804). Revealing how the radical antislavery politics of this seminal event have been suppressed and ignored in historical and cultural records over the past two hundred years, Sibylle Fischer contends that revolutionary antislavery and its subsequent disavowal are central to the formation and understanding of Western modernity. She develops a powerful argument that the denial of revolutionary antislavery eventually became a crucial ingredient in a range of hegemonic thought, including Creole nationalism in the Caribbean and G. W. F. Hegel's master-slave dialectic.Fischer draws on history, literary scholarship, political theory, philosophy, and psychoanalytic theory to examine a range of material, including Haitian political and legal documents and nineteenth-century Cuban and Dominican literature and art. She demonstrates that at a time when racial taxonomies were beginning to mutate into scientific racism and racist biology, the Haitian revolutionaries recognized the question of race as political. Yet, as the cultural records of neighboring Cuba and the Dominican Republic show, the story of the Haitian Revolution has been told as one outside politics and beyond human language, as a tale of barbarism and unspeakable violence. From the time of the revolution onward, the story has been confined to the margins of history: to rumors, oral histories, and confidential letters. Fischer maintains that without accounting for revolutionary antislavery and its subsequent disavowal, Western modernity-including its hierarchy of values, depoliticization of social goals having to do with racial differences, and privileging of claims of national sovereignty-cannot be fully understood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aBlackszCubaxHistory. 0aBlackszDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aLiterature and history. 0aSlave insurrections. 0aSlavery in literature